                        <div type="translation">
            <p>Front: The people and the Roman merchants... crown with a golden crown... son of Apollonios... king... moderation and… to the fatherland</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The text is an honorific inscription commemorating the crowning of a man, possibly
                    Apollonios, or the son of an Apollonios. The crown might be made of gold, and it is possibly the city and the
                    Roman merchants who crown him. If Sterrett’s fuller transcription is accurate,
                    then it is a local king who received the honor. If not, then he is at the very
                    least an aristocrat, as the honor is prestigious. The word πατρίδι implies
                    Apollonius was local. Crowns were made of a variety of materials, and golden
                    crowns were the most expensive, and therefore most prized. It stands to reason
                    then that Apollonius was honored for some outstanding service to the city. The
                    inscription can be dated between the late first century BCE and the early first
                    century CE or the early first century CE based on paleography: the elongated
                    alphas with the broken cross-bar, the cursive omega and rho, and the use of
                    serifs are all indicators of this time period.</p></div>
            

